{{distinguish|Bwa languages (Gur)}} {{Infobox language family |name=Bati–Angba |altname=Bwa |ethnicity= |region= |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] ([[Guthrie classification of Bantu languages#Zone C|Zone C.40]]) |fam6=[[Boan languages|Boan]] |fam7=Bomokandian |glotto=late1250 |glottorefname=Late Bomokandian }}
The '''Bati–Angba''' or '''Bwa languages''' are a clade of [[Bantu language]]s, about half of Zone C.40 in Guthrie's classification. According to Nurse & Philippson (2003), these languages form a valid node. They are: : [[Bwa language|Bwa]] (Yewu, Benge–Baati) – [[Pagibete language|Pagibete]], [[Kango language (Bas-Uélé District)|Kango]]<!--included in Ehret-->, [[Bango language|Bango]] (Babango), [[Ngelima language|Ngelima]] (Angba)
In addition, Nurse & Philippson report that Bati–Angba may be a part of [[Komo–Bira languages]]. The proposal is called '''[[Boan languages|Boan]]'''.
==Footnotes== {{reflist}}
==References== *Nurse & Philippson (2003), ''The Bantu Languages.''
