hip that was wrecked near [[Llandudno, Cape Town|Llandudno]], [[Cape Town]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Gribble |first=John |year=2006 |title=The Sad Case of the ss Maori |work=Heritage at Risk Special Edition |publisher=International Council on Monuments and Sites |pages=41–43 |url=http://www.international.icomos.org/risk/2006/fulldocan.pdf#page=67}}</ref> | |- |''[[Meisho Maru No. 38]]'' |1982 |A [[fishing trawler]] that sank near [[Cape Aghulas]]. |{{coord|34|49|S|19|59|E|name=Meisho Maru No. 38}} |- |''[[Nolloth]]'' | |A [[coastal trading vessel]] that sunk near [[Olifantsbos Bay]]. |{{Coord|34|16|S|18|23|E|name=Nolloth}} |- |''[[Pantalis A Lemos]]'' |1978 |A [[bulk carrier]] that sank near [[Saldanha Bay]]. |{{coord|33|9|S|18|1|E|name=Pantalis A Lemos}} |- | {{HMS|Pelorus|J291|6}} |12 November 1994 |A British {{sclass-|Algerine|minesweeper}} built in 1943. It was renamed SAS ''Pietermarizburg'' in 1947, and at the end of its career was scuttled to make an [[artificial reef]] at Miller's Point near [[Simon's Town]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Baakens |first=Hugh |url=http://www.theherald.co.za/colarc/hughb/hb240602.htm |title=Highs and lows of a once proud vessel |work=The Herald Online |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20021202113624/http://www.theherald.co.za/colarc/hughb/hb240602.htm |archivedate = 2 December 2002}}</ref> | |- | {{ship||Phoenix|1810 ship|2}} |19 July 1829 |A merchant vessel that was wrecked near [[Simon's Town]]. |{{coord|34|11.388|S|18|26.898|E|name=Phoenix (1810 ship)}} |- | {{ship|SAS|President Kruger|F150|6}} |18 February 1982 |A South African [[frigate]] that sank in deep water after a collision with its refueling ship, {{ship|SAS|Tafelberg}}.<ref name=ambassador>{{cite web|publisher=[[South African Navy]]|author=Wessels, André |url=http://www.navy.mil.za/aboutus/history/ambassadors.htm|title=Flag-Showing Cruises By South African Warships, 1922–2002 |accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref> |{{coord|35|15|S|17|21|E|name=SAS President Kruger (F15